# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-documentdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] A document database natively stores JSON data.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] DocumentDB provides single document lookups, index scans, regular expression queries, and aggregations.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] It can create single-field, compound, and multi-key indexes to improve the performance of query patterns.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] Reads from the indexes on the primary instance are read-after-write consistent and users can delete or create new indexes at any time.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] DocumentDB was an enhancement to the Amazon Aurora relational database system, specifically the PostgreSQL-compatible edition.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] Its architecture separates storage and computing so that each layer can scale independently, though the system is limited to a single writable primary.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] Amazon DocumentDB, through Aurora PostgreSQL, uses the Aurora Storage Engine, originally built for the MySQL relational database.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] This storage engine is distributed, fault-tolerant, self-healing, and durable, which it maintains by replicating data six ways across three AWS Availability Zones (AZs).
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] Amazon DocumentDB databases cannot span AWS Regions or span cloud providers, nor can Amazon DocumentDB run on-premises.
[src:aws-documentdb/amazon-documentdb] The system can support up to 15 low-latency readable replicas and continuously backs up all changes to Amazon S3.
[src:aws-documentdb/bson] The topmost element in the structure must be of type BSON object and contains 1 or more elements, where an element consists of a field name, a type, and a value.
[src:aws-documentdb/bson] An important differentiator to JSON is that BSON contains types not present in JSON (e.g. datetime, byte array, and proper IEEE 754 floats) and offers type-strict handling for several numeric types instead of a universal "number" type.
[src:aws-documentdb/bson] For situations where these additional types need to be represented in a textual way, MongoDB's Extended JSON format can be used.
[src:aws-documentdb/bson] Compared to JSON, BSON is designed to be efficient both in storage space and scan-speed.
[src:aws-documentdb/bson] Large elements in a BSON document are prefixed with a length field to facilitate scanning.
[src:aws-documentdb/bson] In some cases, BSON will use more space than JSON due to the length prefixes and explicit array indices.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:aws-documentdb/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:aws-documentdb/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:aws-documentdb/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:aws-documentdb/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:aws-documentdb/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:aws-documentdb/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:aws-documentdb/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The American software company 10gen began developing MongoDB in 2007 as a component of a planned platform-as-a-service product.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In 2009, the company shifted to an open-source development model and began offering commercial support and other services.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In 2013, 10gen changed its name to MongoDB Inc.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] On October 20, 2017, MongoDB became a publicly traded company, listed on NASDAQ as MDB with an IPO price of $24 per share.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] On November 8, 2018, with the stable release 4.0.4, the software's license changed from AGPL 3.0 to SSPL.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] On October 30, 2019, MongoDB teamed with Alibaba Cloud to offer Alibaba Cloud customers a MongoDB-as-a-service solution.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Customers can use the managed offering from Alibaba's global data centers.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In December 2025, a major exploit was discovered and titled as "MongoBleed".
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] This exploit led to the compromise of many corporate servers.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] As of May 2025, MongoDB was the fifth most popular database software.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] It focuses mostly on managing large databases of unstructured, "messy" data.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] It's typically used for mobile and web apps that commonly use unstructured databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] As of 2024, there were 50,000 MongoDB customers.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB was originally best known as a NoSQL database product.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The company released a database as-a-service product called Atlas in 2016 that became 70 percent of MongoDB's revenue by 2024.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Over time, MongoDB added analytics, transactional databases, encryption, vector databases, ACID, migration features, and other enterprise tools.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Initially, the MongoDB software was free and open source under the AGPL license.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB adopted an SSPL (server side public license) for future releases starting in 2018.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB implements its own query language called *Mongo Query Language* (MQL).
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB supports field, range query and regular-expression searches.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Queries can return specific fields of documents and also include user-defined JavaScript functions.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Queries can also be configured to return a random sample of results of a given size.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Fields in a MongoDB document can be indexed with primary and secondary indices.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB provides high availability with replica sets.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] A replica set consists of two or more copies of the data.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Each replica-set member may act in the role of primary or secondary replica at any time.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] All writes and reads are done on the primary replica by default.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Secondary replicas maintain a copy of the data of the primary using built-in replication.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] When a primary replica fails, the replica set automatically conducts an election process to determine which secondary should become the primary.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Secondaries can optionally serve read operations, but that data is only eventually consistent by default.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] If the replicated MongoDB deployment only has a single secondary member, a separate daemon called an arbiter must be added to the set.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] It has the single responsibility of resolving the election of the new primary.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] As a consequence, an ideal distributed MongoDB deployment requires at least three separate servers, even in the case of just one primary and one secondary.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB scales horizontally using sharding.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The user chooses a shard key, which determines how the data in a collection will be distributed.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The data is split into ranges (based on the shard key) and distributed across multiple shards, which are masters with one or more replicas.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Alternatively, the shard key can be hashed to map to a shard – enabling an even data distribution.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB can run over multiple servers, balancing the load or duplicating data to keep the system functional in case of hardware failure.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB can be used as a file system, called GridFS, with load-balancing and data-replication features over multiple machines for storing files.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] This function, called a grid file system, is included with MongoDB drivers.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB exposes functions for file manipulation and content to developers.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] GridFS can be accessed using the mongofiles utility or plugins for Nginx and lighttpd.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] GridFS divides a file into parts, or chunks, and stores each of those chunks as a separate document.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB provides three ways to perform aggregation: the aggregation pipeline (preferred), the map-reduce function (deprecated as of MongoDB 5.0) and single-purpose aggregation methods.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Map-reduce can be used for batch processing of data and aggregation operations.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] However, according to MongoDB's documentation, the aggregation pipeline provides better performance for most aggregation operations.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The aggregation framework enables users to obtain results similar to those returned by queries that include the SQL GROUP BY clause.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Aggregation operators can be strung together to form a pipeline, analogous to Unix pipes.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The aggregation framework includes the $lookup operator, which can join documents from multiple collections, as well as statistical operators such as standard deviation.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB supports fixed-size collections called capped collections.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] This type of collection maintains insertion order and, once the specified size has been reached, behaves like a circular queue.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB supports multi-document ACID transactions since the 4.0 release in June 2018.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] As of October 2018, MongoDB is released under the Server Side Public License (SSPL), a non-free license developed by the project.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] It replaces the GNU Affero General Public License.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In contrast to the AGPL, the SSPL prevents anyone but MongoDB Inc. from making MongoDB "available as a service" without negotiating a separate license from MongoDb Inc.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The license text specifies a condition for making MongoDB which MongoDB Inc. has claimed to be similar to AGPL, but is actually impossible to comply with.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The condition states that "all programs that you use to make the Program" ...
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] "available as a service" must be published under the SSPL.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] However, a core component of MongoDB called WiredTiger is licensed as GPL, and the GPL does not allow redistribution under any license except the GPL.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] This does not apply to the copyright holder (MongoDB Inc.).
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Since MongoDB's SSPL adoption in 2018, no one has ever provided MongoDB as a paid service under the SSPL license (including MongoDB Inc.).
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The SSPL was submitted for certification to the Open Source Initiative but later withdrawn.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In January 2021, the Open Source Initiative stated that SSPL is not an open source license.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The language drivers are available under an Apache License.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In addition, MongoDB Inc. offers proprietary licenses for MongoDB.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The last versions licensed as AGPL version 3 are 4.0.3 (stable) and 4.1.4.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] MongoDB has been removed from the Debian, Fedora and Red Hat Enterprise Linux distributions because of the licensing change.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Fedora determined that the SSPL version 1 is not a free software license because it is "intentionally crafted to be aggressively discriminatory" towards commercial users.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Because of MongoDB's default security configuration, which allows any user full access to the database, data from tens of thousands of MongoDB installations has been stolen.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Furthermore, many MongoDB servers have been held for ransom.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In September 2017, Davi Ottenheimer head of product security at MongoDB, proclaimed that measures had been taken to defend against these risks.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In some failure scenarios in which an application can access two distinct MongoDB processes that cannot access each other, it is possible for MongoDB to return stale reads.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] It is also possible for MongoDB to roll back writes that have been acknowledged.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The issue was addressed in version 3.4.0, released in November 2016, and applied to earlier releases from v3.2.12 onward.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Before version 2.2, locks were implemented on a per-server-process basis.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] With version 2.2, locks were implemented at the database level.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Beginning with version 3.0, pluggable storage engines are available, and each storage engine may implement locks differently.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] With MongoDB 3.0, locks are implemented at the collection level for the MMAPv1 storage engine, while the WiredTiger storage engine uses an optimistic concurrency protocol that effectively provides document-level locking.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Even with versions prior to 3.0, one approach to increase concurrency is to use sharding.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] In some situations, reads and writes will yield their locks.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] If MongoDB predicts that a page is unlikely to be in memory, operations will yield their lock while the pages load.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The use of lock yielding expanded greatly in version 2.2.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Until version 3.3.11, MongoDB could not perform collation-based sorting and was limited to bytewise comparison via memcmp, which would not provide correct ordering for many non-English languages when used with a Unicode encoding.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Prior to MongoDB 4.0, queries against an index were not atomic.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] Documents that were updated while queries was running could be missed.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] The introduction of the snapshot read concern in MongoDB 4.0 eliminated this risk.
[src:aws-documentdb/mongodb] FerretDB is an open source project that converts MongoDB 5.0 wire protocol queries into SQL, allowing clients to query postgreSQL (or other databases) using the Mongo wire protocol.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:aws-documentdb/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
